Add `inThinking` and `thinkingStartMs` tracking fields to the `ToolState` interface and `createToolState()` factory in `apps/server/src/services/runtimes/claude-code/agent-types.ts`.

## Implementation Steps

### 1. Update ToolState interface

Add two new fields to the `ToolState` interface:

```typescript
export interface ToolState {
  inTool: boolean;
  currentToolName: string;
  currentToolId: string;
  taskToolInput: string;
  inThinking: boolean;       // NEW: true when inside a thinking content block
  thinkingStartMs: number;   // NEW: timestamp when thinking block started
  appendTaskInput: (chunk: string) => void;
  resetTaskInput: () => void;
  setToolState: (tool: boolean, name: string, id: string) => void;
}
```

### 2. Update createToolState() factory

Add getter/setter closures for the new fields, following the existing pattern with closure variables and getters:

```typescript
export function createToolState(): ToolState {
  let inTool = false;
  let currentToolName = '';
  let currentToolId = '';
  let taskToolInput = '';
  let inThinking = false;      // NEW
  let thinkingStartMs = 0;     // NEW
  return {
    get inTool() { return inTool; },
    get currentToolName() { return currentToolName; },
    get currentToolId() { return currentToolId; },
    get taskToolInput() { return taskToolInput; },
    get inThinking() { return inThinking; },             // NEW
    set inThinking(v: boolean) { inThinking = v; },      // NEW
    get thinkingStartMs() { return thinkingStartMs; },   // NEW
    set thinkingStartMs(v: number) { thinkingStartMs = v; }, // NEW
    appendTaskInput: (chunk: string) => { taskToolInput += chunk; },
    resetTaskInput: () => { taskToolInput = ''; },
    setToolState: (tool: boolean, name: string, id: string) => {
      inTool = tool; currentToolName = name; currentToolId = id;
    },
  };
}
```

Note: The existing fields (`inTool`, `currentToolName`, etc.) use only getters and rely on `setToolState()` for mutations. For `inThinking` and `thinkingStartMs`, direct property assignment in the mapper is simpler, so use getter+setter pairs.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `ToolState` interface includes `inThinking: boolean` and `thinkingStartMs: number`
- [ ] `createToolState()` initializes `inThinking = false` and `thinkingStartMs = 0`
- [ ] `inThinking` and `thinkingStartMs` are readable and writable on the returned object
- [ ] `pnpm typecheck` passes
- [ ] Existing tests that use `createToolState()` or mock `ToolState` still compile and pass

Add `thinking` content block handling to the `mapSdkMessage()` async generator in `apps/server/src/services/runtimes/claude-code/sdk-event-mapper.ts`. This maps SDK thinking events to `thinking_delta` DorkOS stream events.

## Implementation Steps

### 1. Add thinking branch to content_block_start (before the existing tool_use check at line 87)

Inside the `eventType === 'content_block_start'` block, before the existing `contentBlock?.type === 'tool_use'` check:

```typescript
if (eventType === 'content_block_start') {
  const contentBlock = event.content_block as Record<string, unknown> | undefined;
  // Handle thinking block start
  if (contentBlock?.type === 'thinking') {
    toolState.inThinking = true;
    toolState.thinkingStartMs = Date.now();
    return;  // No event emitted on start — first delta triggers client-side creation
  }
  if (contentBlock?.type === 'tool_use') {
    // ... existing tool_use handling unchanged
  }
}
```

The `return` is important: no stream event is emitted for thinking block start. The client creates the thinking part when the first `thinking_delta` arrives.

### 2. Add thinking_delta branch to content_block_delta (before the existing text_delta check at line 101)

Inside the `eventType === 'content_block_delta'` block:

```typescript
} else if (eventType === 'content_block_delta') {
  const delta = event.delta as Record<string, unknown> | undefined;
  // Handle thinking delta
  if (delta?.type === 'thinking_delta' && toolState.inThinking) {
    yield {
      type: 'thinking_delta',
      data: { text: delta.thinking as string },
    };
  } else if (delta?.type === 'text_delta' && !toolState.inTool) {
    yield { type: 'text_delta', data: { text: delta.text as string } };
  } else if (delta?.type === 'input_json_delta' && toolState.inTool) {
    // ... existing input_json_delta handling unchanged
  }
}
```

Key detail: The SDK's thinking_delta uses `delta.thinking` (not `delta.text`) for the thinking text content. This is the Anthropic SDK convention for thinking content blocks.

### 3. Add thinking block stop handling to content_block_stop (before existing tool handling at line 118)

Inside the `eventType === 'content_block_stop'` block:

```typescript
} else if (eventType === 'content_block_stop') {
  // Handle thinking block stop
  if (toolState.inThinking) {
    toolState.inThinking = false;
    return;  // No event emitted — client detects completion via first text_delta
  }
  if (toolState.inTool) {
    // ... existing tool handling unchanged
  }
}
```

No stream event is emitted for thinking block stop. The client detects the thinking-to-text phase transition implicitly when the first `text_delta` arrives after thinking deltas. This follows the single-event-type design decision.

## Event Flow Summary

SDK events -> DorkOS stream events:
- `content_block_start(thinking)` -> (no event, sets toolState.inThinking = true)
- `content_block_delta(thinking_delta)` -> `{ type: 'thinking_delta', data: { text } }`
- `content_block_stop` (while inThinking) -> (no event, sets toolState.inThinking = false)
- `content_block_delta(text_delta)` -> `{ type: 'text_delta', data: { text } }` (unchanged)

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `content_block_start` with `type: 'thinking'` sets `toolState.inThinking = true` and `thinkingStartMs` to current time
- [ ] `content_block_delta` with `type: 'thinking_delta'` yields `{ type: 'thinking_delta', data: { text: delta.thinking } }` when `toolState.inThinking` is true
- [ ] `content_block_delta` with `type: 'thinking_delta'` is silently dropped when `toolState.inThinking` is false
- [ ] `content_block_stop` when `toolState.inThinking` resets the flag to false and returns without yielding
- [ ] Existing `text_delta`, `tool_use`, and `input_json_delta` handling is unchanged
- [ ] No regressions in existing sdk-event-mapper tests
- [ ] `pnpm typecheck` passes

Add `thinking` content block handling to the JSONL transcript parser in `apps/server/src/services/runtimes/claude-code/transcript-parser.ts` so thinking blocks persist across page reloads.

## Implementation Steps

### 1. Add `thinking` field to the ContentBlock interface (line 36)

The SDK JSONL stores thinking content in a `thinking` field (not `text`). Update the `ContentBlock` interface:

```typescript
export interface ContentBlock {
  type: string;
  text?: string;
  thinking?: string;  // NEW: thinking content from SDK JSONL
  name?: string;
  id?: string;
  input?: Record<string, unknown>;
  tool_use_id?: string;
  content?: string | ContentBlock[];
}
```

### 2. Add thinking branch to the assistant content block loop (line 344)

In the `parseTranscript()` function, inside the `for (const block of contentBlocks)` loop that processes assistant message content blocks, add a `thinking` branch BEFORE the existing `text` check. Thinking blocks must appear before text blocks in the parts array to match the streaming order:

```typescript
for (const block of contentBlocks) {
  // NEW: Handle thinking content blocks
  if (block.type === 'thinking' && block.thinking) {
    // SDK JSONL uses `thinking` field, not `text`, for thinking content.
    // Rendered collapsed by default in history (isStreaming: false).
    parts.push({
      type: 'thinking',
      text: block.thinking,
      isStreaming: false,
    } as MessagePart);
  } else if (block.type === 'text' && block.text) {
    const lastPart = parts[parts.length - 1];
    if (lastPart && lastPart.type === 'text') {
      lastPart.text += '\n' + block.text;
    } else {
      parts.push({ type: 'text', text: block.text });
    }
  } else if (block.type === 'tool_use' && block.name && block.id) {
    // ... existing tool_use handling unchanged
  }
}
```

The `as MessagePart` cast is needed because the `ThinkingPart` type includes `isStreaming` which is optional in the schema. The discriminated union will validate at runtime via the `type: 'thinking'` discriminator.

### 3. Handle edge cases

- **Empty thinking blocks**: `block.thinking` could be an empty string `''`. The condition `block.thinking` (truthy check) correctly skips empty thinking blocks. This is the desired behavior - empty thinking blocks have no content to display.
- **Multiple thinking blocks per turn**: Each thinking block becomes a separate `ThinkingPart` in the parts array. No special handling needed.
- **Thinking blocks without `thinking` field**: The `block.thinking` check prevents creation of invalid parts with empty text.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `ContentBlock` interface includes `thinking?: string` field
- [ ] Assistant messages with `{ type: 'thinking', thinking: 'reasoning text...' }` content blocks produce `ThinkingPart` entries in the parts array
- [ ] `ThinkingPart` entries have `isStreaming: false` (history is always collapsed)
- [ ] Thinking parts appear before text parts in the parts array (matching streaming order)
- [ ] Empty thinking blocks (`thinking: ''`) are skipped gracefully
- [ ] Messages without thinking blocks parse identically to before (no regression)
- [ ] `pnpm typecheck` passes
- [ ] Existing transcript-parser tests still pass

Add `thinking_delta` case to the client stream event handler switch statement in `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/model/stream-event-handler.ts`, and modify the `text_delta` case to finalize in-progress thinking blocks.

## Implementation Steps

### 1. Add `thinkingStartRef` to StreamEventDeps interface (line 22)

Add a new ref to track when thinking started for elapsed time calculation:

```typescript
interface StreamEventDeps {
  currentPartsRef: React.MutableRefObject<MessagePart[]>;
  thinkingStartRef: React.MutableRefObject<number | null>;  // NEW
  assistantCreatedRef: React.MutableRefObject<boolean>;
  // ... rest unchanged
}
```

### 2. Destructure the new ref in createStreamEventHandler (around line 72)

Add `thinkingStartRef` to the destructuring:

```typescript
const {
  currentPartsRef,
  thinkingStartRef,  // NEW
  assistantCreatedRef,
  // ... rest unchanged
} = deps;
```

### 3. Import ThinkingDelta type

Add to the import from `@dorkos/shared/types` at the top:

```typescript
import type {
  TextDelta,
  ThinkingDelta,  // NEW
  ToolCallEvent,
  // ... rest unchanged
} from '@dorkos/shared/types';
```

### 4. Add `thinking_delta` case (before the `text_delta` case, around line 157)

Add a new case in the switch statement. Place it before `text_delta` for logical grouping (thinking happens before text in a turn):

```typescript
case 'thinking_delta': {
  const { text } = data as ThinkingDelta;
  const parts = currentPartsRef.current;
  const lastPart = parts[parts.length - 1];

  if (lastPart && lastPart.type === 'thinking') {
    // Append to existing thinking part (immutable update)
    currentPartsRef.current = [
      ...parts.slice(0, -1),
      { ...lastPart, text: (lastPart as { text: string }).text + text, isStreaming: true } as MessagePart,
    ];
  } else {
    // New thinking part — record start time
    if (!thinkingStartRef.current) {
      thinkingStartRef.current = Date.now();
    }
    const partId = `thinking-part-${parts.length}`;
    currentPartsRef.current = [
      ...parts,
      { type: 'thinking', text, isStreaming: true, _partId: partId } as MessagePart,
    ];
  }
  updateAssistantMessage(assistantId);
  break;
}
```

This follows the same immutable update pattern used by the `text_delta` case. The `_partId` provides a stable React key for the thinking part during streaming.

### 5. Modify `text_delta` case to finalize thinking (at the beginning of the existing case)

When the first `text_delta` arrives after thinking deltas, mark the thinking part as complete with elapsed time:

```typescript
case 'text_delta': {
  // Finalize thinking if transitioning from thinking to text
  const parts = currentPartsRef.current;
  const thinkingIdx = parts.findIndex(
    (p) => p.type === 'thinking' && (p as { isStreaming?: boolean }).isStreaming
  );
  if (thinkingIdx !== -1) {
    const thinkingPart = parts[thinkingIdx];
    const elapsed = thinkingStartRef.current
      ? Date.now() - thinkingStartRef.current
      : undefined;
    currentPartsRef.current = [
      ...parts.slice(0, thinkingIdx),
      { ...thinkingPart, isStreaming: false, elapsedMs: elapsed } as MessagePart,
      ...parts.slice(thinkingIdx + 1),
    ];
    thinkingStartRef.current = null;
  }
  // ... existing text_delta logic continues (use currentPartsRef.current, not stale `parts`)
  const { text } = data as TextDelta;
  const currentParts = currentPartsRef.current;
  const lastPart = currentParts[currentParts.length - 1];
  // ... rest of existing text_delta logic
}
```

IMPORTANT: After modifying `currentPartsRef.current` for thinking finalization, the rest of the text_delta logic must re-read from `currentPartsRef.current` (not a stale `parts` variable).

### 6. Reset thinkingStartRef in the `done` case

In the `done` case handler, add cleanup:

```typescript
case 'done': {
  // ... existing done logic
  thinkingStartRef.current = null;  // NEW: reset thinking timer
  streamStartTimeRef.current = null;
  // ... rest unchanged
}
```

### 7. Update the calling site

The hook that creates `StreamEventDeps` (likely in `use-chat-session.ts` or similar) must provide `thinkingStartRef`. Add:

```typescript
const thinkingStartRef = useRef<number | null>(null);
```

And pass it in the deps object.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] First `thinking_delta` creates a new `ThinkingPart` with `isStreaming: true` in the parts array
- [ ] Subsequent `thinking_delta` events append text to the existing `ThinkingPart` (immutable update)
- [ ] First `text_delta` after thinking marks `ThinkingPart.isStreaming = false` and sets `elapsedMs`
- [ ] Parts array ordering: thinking part precedes text part
- [ ] `thinkingStartRef` is reset in `done` handler
- [ ] `pnpm typecheck` passes
- [ ] No regression in existing stream-event-handler behavior for text_delta, tool_call_*, subagent_*, etc.

Create a new `ThinkingBlock.tsx` component at `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/ui/ThinkingBlock.tsx` with progressive disclosure behavior matching the SubagentBlock pattern.

## File Location

`apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/ui/ThinkingBlock.tsx`

This is co-located with `SubagentBlock.tsx`, `StreamingText.tsx`, and `ToolCallCard.tsx` in the chat feature's UI segment.

## Props Interface

```typescript
interface ThinkingBlockProps {
  text: string;
  isStreaming: boolean;
  elapsedMs?: number;
}
```

## Four Visual States

1. **Streaming** (`isStreaming === true`): Open block with breathing "Thinking..." label and live streaming text content. Block cannot be collapsed during streaming.
2. **Collapsing** (transition from streaming to complete): Animated height collapse via `AnimatePresence`.
3. **Collapsed** (`isStreaming === false`, `!expanded`): "Thought for Xs" chip with chevron expand/collapse affordance.
4. **Expanded** (`isStreaming === false`, `expanded`): Full thinking content visible, capped at `max-h-64 overflow-y-auto`.

## Complete Implementation

```typescript
import { useState, useRef, useEffect } from 'react';
import { motion, AnimatePresence } from 'motion/react';
import { Brain, ChevronDown } from 'lucide-react';
import { cn } from '@/layers/shared/lib';

interface ThinkingBlockProps {
  text: string;
  isStreaming: boolean;
  elapsedMs?: number;
}

/** Format elapsed milliseconds to a human-readable duration string. */
function formatThinkingDuration(ms: number): string {
  if (ms < 1000) return '<1s';
  const seconds = Math.round(ms / 1000);
  if (seconds < 60) return `${seconds}s`;
  const minutes = Math.floor(seconds / 60);
  const remainingSeconds = seconds % 60;
  return `${minutes}m ${remainingSeconds}s`;
}

/** Collapsible block displaying Claude's extended thinking content. */
export function ThinkingBlock({ text, isStreaming, elapsedMs }: ThinkingBlockProps) {
  const [expanded, setExpanded] = useState(isStreaming);
  const wasStreamingRef = useRef(isStreaming);

  // Auto-collapse when streaming transitions to complete
  useEffect(() => {
    if (wasStreamingRef.current && !isStreaming) {
      setExpanded(false);
    }
    wasStreamingRef.current = isStreaming;
  }, [isStreaming]);

  // Force expanded during streaming (cannot collapse while thinking)
  const isOpen = isStreaming || expanded;

  const durationLabel = elapsedMs
    ? `Thought for ${formatThinkingDuration(elapsedMs)}`
    : 'Thought';

  return (
    <div
      className="bg-muted/50 mt-px rounded-msg-tool border border-l-2 border-muted-foreground/20 text-sm shadow-msg-tool first:mt-1"
      data-testid="thinking-block"
      data-streaming={isStreaming}
    >
      <button
        onClick={() => !isStreaming && setExpanded(!expanded)}
        className={cn(
          'flex w-full items-center gap-2 px-3 py-1',
          isStreaming && 'cursor-default'
        )}
        aria-expanded={isStreaming ? true : expanded}
        aria-label={isStreaming ? 'Thinking in progress' : durationLabel}
        disabled={isStreaming}
      >
        <Brain className="size-(--size-icon-xs) text-muted-foreground" />
        {isStreaming ? (
          <span className="text-3xs font-mono text-muted-foreground animate-pulse">
            Thinking...
          </span>
        ) : (
          <span className="text-3xs font-mono text-muted-foreground">
            {durationLabel}
          </span>
        )}
        {!isStreaming && (
          <motion.div
            animate={{ rotate: expanded ? 180 : 0 }}
            transition={{ type: 'spring', stiffness: 400, damping: 30 }}
            className="ml-auto"
          >
            <ChevronDown className="size-(--size-icon-xs)" />
          </motion.div>
        )}
      </button>
      <AnimatePresence initial={false}>
        {isOpen && (
          <motion.div
            initial={{ height: 0, opacity: 0 }}
            animate={{ height: 'auto', opacity: 1 }}
            exit={{ height: 0, opacity: 0 }}
            transition={{ duration: 0.3, ease: [0.4, 0, 0.2, 1] }}
            className="overflow-hidden"
          >
            <div className="border-t px-3 pt-1 pb-3">
              <pre
                className={cn(
                  'text-xs text-muted-foreground whitespace-pre-wrap',
                  !isStreaming && 'max-h-64 overflow-y-auto'
                )}
              >
                {text}
              </pre>
            </div>
          </motion.div>
        )}
      </AnimatePresence>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Design Decisions

- **Brain icon** from lucide-react for the thinking header, distinguishing from SubagentBlock's status icons.
- **`animate-pulse`** on the "Thinking..." label provides a breathing effect (CSS, not JS). This is a standard Tailwind utility matching the spec's 2s ease-in-out requirement.
- **`border-l-2 border-muted-foreground/20`** provides the left accent border called for in the spec.
- **`pre` element with `whitespace-pre-wrap`** for thinking content — plain text rendering with no markdown/HTML parsing (security consideration: thinking content is rendered as plain text only).
- **`max-h-64 overflow-y-auto`** only applied when NOT streaming to allow natural growth during streaming.
- **`disabled` on button during streaming** prevents user from collapsing during active thinking.
- **ChevronDown rotation** uses spring animation matching SubagentBlock exactly (`stiffness: 400, damping: 30`).
- **AnimatePresence** expand/collapse animation matches SubagentBlock (`duration: 0.3, ease: [0.4, 0, 0.2, 1]`).

## ARIA Semantics

- Header button: `aria-expanded` reflects current state, `aria-label` describes block purpose.
- Button is `disabled` during streaming to indicate non-interactive state.
- Content uses `<pre>` (landmark-neutral) for thinking text.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] File created at `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/ui/ThinkingBlock.tsx`
- [ ] Renders "Thinking..." label with pulse animation when `isStreaming = true`
- [ ] Renders "Thought for Xs" chip when `isStreaming = false` with `elapsedMs`
- [ ] Content is visible when streaming
- [ ] Content auto-collapses when `isStreaming` transitions from true to false
- [ ] Click on collapsed chip expands content
- [ ] Click on expanded chip collapses content
- [ ] Cannot collapse during streaming (button disabled)
- [ ] Long content has `max-h-64 overflow-y-auto` when not streaming
- [ ] ARIA: `aria-expanded` reflects state
- [ ] Brain icon distinguishes from SubagentBlock
- [ ] `pnpm typecheck` passes

Add a `thinking` branch to the parts map dispatcher in `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/ui/message/AssistantMessageContent.tsx` so thinking parts are rendered as `ThinkingBlock` components.

## Implementation Steps

### 1. Add ThinkingBlock import

Add to the imports at the top of the file:

```typescript
import { ThinkingBlock } from '../ThinkingBlock';
```

### 2. Add thinking branch to parts.map() (before the text branch)

Inside the `parts.map((part, i) => { ... })` callback, add a `thinking` check BEFORE the `text` check. Thinking blocks should always render above text in the message, and since the parts array already has thinking before text, this ordering is natural:

```typescript
{parts.map((part, i) => {
  // NEW: Thinking block — before text so it renders above response
  if (part.type === 'thinking') {
    return (
      <ThinkingBlock
        key={(part as { _partId?: string })._partId ?? `thinking-${i}`}
        text={(part as { text: string }).text}
        isStreaming={(part as { isStreaming?: boolean }).isStreaming ?? false}
        elapsedMs={(part as { elapsedMs?: number }).elapsedMs}
      />
    );
  }
  if (part.type === 'text') {
    // ... existing text handling unchanged
  }
  if (part.type === 'subagent') {
    // ... existing subagent handling unchanged
  }
  // ... rest unchanged
})}
```

The `as` casts are needed because `MessagePart` is a discriminated union. When `part.type === 'thinking'`, TypeScript narrows to `ThinkingPart`, but the `_partId` is a client-only streaming extension (not in the schema), so it needs a cast. This matches the existing pattern for `_partId` on text parts (line 122 of the current file).

### 3. Export ThinkingBlock from the feature barrel

If `ThinkingBlock` needs to be accessible from outside the chat feature (unlikely, but check the barrel file pattern), add it to the chat feature's barrel exports. Since it's only used by `AssistantMessageContent` within the same feature, no barrel export is likely needed.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Messages with a `thinking` part render a `ThinkingBlock` component
- [ ] Messages with thinking + text parts render both in correct order (thinking above text)
- [ ] Messages without thinking parts render identically to before (no regression)
- [ ] `_partId` is used as React key when available (streaming), falls back to `thinking-${i}` (history)
- [ ] `isStreaming` defaults to `false` when not present (history case)
- [ ] `pnpm typecheck` passes
- [ ] No visual regression in existing message rendering

Add unit tests to the existing sdk-event-mapper test file for thinking block handling. Tests validate the server-side SDK event to DorkOS stream event mapping.

## Test File

`apps/server/src/services/runtimes/claude-code/__tests__/sdk-event-mapper.test.ts`

Add a new `describe('thinking blocks')` block.

## Test Setup

Use the existing test setup patterns from the file. You will need:

```typescript
import { mapSdkMessage } from '../sdk-event-mapper.js';
import { createToolState } from '../agent-types.js';
import type { AgentSession, ToolState } from '../agent-types.js';
import type { StreamEvent } from '@dorkos/shared/types';

/** Collect all events from the async generator. */
async function collectEvents(
  message: Record<string, unknown>,
  session: AgentSession,
  sessionId: string,
  toolState: ToolState
): Promise<StreamEvent[]> {
  const events: StreamEvent[] = [];
  for await (const event of mapSdkMessage(
    message as any,
    session,
    sessionId,
    toolState
  )) {
    events.push(event);
  }
  return events;
}
```

